"html","id":"ggbePjQG512_text","label":"ggbePjQG512_text","default":"<p>She was talking. Then she wasn't. Not a pause. Not a gasp. Just — nothing. Like someone had reached through the phone and turned her off.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg0tk0FrMit_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"gg0tk0FrMit_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggf0eVLYBd5_text","label":"ggf0eVLYBd5_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:rgba(235, 254, 251, 0);color:rgb(48,48,48);font-size:16px;\">She was talking. Then she wasn't. Not a pause. Not a gasp. Just — nothing. Like someone had reached through the phone and turned her off.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggIk2laqkUT_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggIk2laqkUT_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/ChatGPT_Image_Mar_13_2026_01_11_39_AM.png"},{"type":"html","id":"ggIk2laqkUT_srcSet_mobile_src","label":"ggIk2laqkUT_srcSet_mobile_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggGNtdN_5fe_text","label":"ggGNtdN_5fe_text","default":"<p>Millions of Americans over 50 take blood pressure medication every morning.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Their numbers look controlled on paper.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But they still wake up with a dull pressure behind their eyes. Still crash by 2pm. Still feel like something underneath is quietly, slowly wrong.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If that sounds familiar, keep reading.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggEa6SyQXzV_text","label":"ggEa6SyQXzV_text","default":"<p>Millions of Americans over 50 take blood pressure medication every morning.</p><p>Their numbers look controlled on paper.</p><p>But they still wake up with a dull pressure behind their eyes. Still crash by 2pm. Still feel like something underneath is quietly, slowly wrong.</p><p>If that sounds familiar, keep reading.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggOa5xG3Oor_text","label":"ggOa5xG3Oor_text","default":"<span style=\"font-size:32px;\"><strong>She Was Doing Everything Right</strong></span>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggqISvF__04_text","label":"ggqISvF__04_text","default":"<span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>She Was Doing Everything Right</strong></span>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggKC8prxvsY_text","label":"ggKC8prxvsY_text","default":"<p>My best friend was 54 years old when she died on the phone with me.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>One sentence she was there. Mid-word, she was gone.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I kept saying her name. Over and over. Nothing came back. Just silence and the faint sound of her kitchen.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Her husband found her on the floor two minutes later.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg0GwCUk3IU_text","label":"gg0GwCUk3IU_text","default":"<p>My best friend was 54 years old when she died on the phone with me.</p><p>One sentence she was there. Mid-word, she was gone.</p><p>I kept saying her name. Over and over. Nothing came back. Just silence and the faint sound of her kitchen.</p><p>Her husband found her on the floor two minutes later.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg6r8QWS8SQ_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"gg6r8QWS8SQ_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_1.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggU9dNMdYRS_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggU9dNMdYRS_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/ChatGPT_Image_Mar_20_2026_04_23_48_PM.png"},{"type":"html","id":"ggU9dNMdYRS_srcSet_mobile_src","label":"ggU9dNMdYRS_srcSet_mobile_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_1.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggjoN7aJdBD_text","label":"ggjoN7aJdBD_text","default":"<p>By the time the ambulance arrived, she was already gone. Massive stroke. No warning. No dramatic buildup. Just there, then not.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I fell apart after the funeral. I couldn't sleep. Couldn't eat. Kept replaying that silence in my head at 3am.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But the thing that truly broke me wasn't the grief.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>It was what I found out standing at her graveside.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>She had high blood pressure for years. She took lisinopril every single morning without fail. She did everything her doctor told her to do.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggQ4cLj6FzR_text","label":"ggQ4cLj6FzR_text","default":"<p>By the time the ambulance arrived, she was already gone. Massive stroke. No warning. No dramatic buildup. Just there, then not.</p><p>I fell apart after the funeral. I couldn't sleep. Couldn't eat. Kept replaying that silence in my head at 3am.</p><p>But the thing that truly broke me wasn't the grief.</p><p><strong>It was what I found out standing at her graveside.</strong></p><p>She had high blood pressure for years. She took lisinopril every single morning without fail. She did everything her doctor told her to do.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggy9WF7nWW8_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggy9WF7nWW8_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/ChatGPT_Image_Mar_20_2026_04_23_48_PM.png"},{"type":"html","id":"ggy9WF7nWW8_srcSet_mobile_src","label":"ggy9WF7nWW8_srcSet_mobile_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_2.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggJ1Iwx_Pdz_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggJ1Iwx_Pdz_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_2.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggS4Yq7eI1Q_text","label":"ggS4Yq7eI1Q_text","default":"<p>She still had the headaches. Still got dizzy. Still felt bone-tired by noon every day.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>We just thought that was her life now. That's what getting older felt like.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>She was managing her numbers. And she still died.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That thought followed me home.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Three days after the funeral, I drove to a doctor for the first time in years. I sat in that waiting room shaking. Palms wet. Telling myself I was probably fine.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Absolutely terrified I wasn't.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The tests came back. I wasn't fine.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>High blood pressure. Pre-diabetes. Triglycerides over 250.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The doctor barely looked up. He picked up his prescription pad and wrote it down in one motion.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Lisinopril.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I stared at that word on the paper for a long, long time. The exact same pill my friend had taken every morning. The pill she was still taking the day she died.</p><p>He told me to cut the salt and come back in three months.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Like it was nothing. Like we were done here.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I walked to my car, sat down, and cried until I couldn't see the steering wheel.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggRAMuKAHXQ_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggRAMuKAHXQ_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/3.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggoV_AqVrW-_text","label":"ggoV_AqVrW-_text","default":"<p>I made a decision that day. Not a quiet one. A hard one.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>I lost nearly 50 pounds.</strong> I went from sedentary and depressed to hiking over 8 miles at a stretch. I got every preventative exam I had been avoiding for years. I took the lisinopril every morning. Ate cleaner. Moved my body every single day without exception.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I did everything right. I did more than everything right.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>And I still felt wrong.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>A pressure behind my eyes every morning when I woke up. Headaches that sat there all day like a fist pressing against the back of my skull. An afternoon exhaustion that knocked into me like a wall, no matter how much sleep I got the night before. A mental fog I kept telling myself was just aging.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I kept thinking about my friend.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I kept wondering if I was on the same road. Just further back.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggnvkfzFTNf_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggnvkfzFTNf_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_3.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggD5yi8Bmkh_text","label":"ggD5yi8Bmkh_text","default":"<p>She still had the headaches. Still got dizzy. Still felt bone-tired by noon every day.</p><p>We just thought that was her life now. That's what getting older felt like.</p><p><strong>She was managing her numbers. And she still died.</strong></p><p>That thought followed me home.</p><p>Three days after the funeral, I drove to a doctor for the first time in years. I sat in that waiting room shaking. Palms wet. Telling myself I was probably fine. Absolutely terrified I wasn't.</p><p>The tests came back. I wasn't fine.</p><p><strong>High blood pressure. Pre-diabetes. Triglycerides over 250.</strong></p><p>The doctor barely looked up. He picked up his prescription pad and wrote it down in one motion.</p><p>Lisinopril.</p><p>I stared at that word on the paper for a long, long time. The exact same pill my friend had taken every morning. The pill she was still taking the day she died.</p><p>He told me to cut the salt and come back in three months.</p><p>Like it was nothing. Like we were done here.</p><p>I walked to my car, sat down, and cried until I couldn't see the steering wheel.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg9ekF5ICdk_text","label":"gg9ekF5ICdk_text","default":"<p><strong>What Your Doctor Never Explained</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggZ-dTEIghd_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggZ-dTEIghd_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/ChatGPT_Image_Mar_20_2026_04_23_48_PM.png"},{"type":"html","id":"ggZ-dTEIghd_srcSet_mobile_src","label":"ggZ-dTEIghd_srcSet_mobile_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/3.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggCqja4iP02_text","label":"ggCqja4iP02_text","default":"<p>I made a decision that day. Not a quiet one. A hard one.</p><p><strong>I lost nearly 50 pounds.</strong> I went from sedentary and depressed to hiking over 8 miles at a stretch. I got every preventative exam I had been avoiding for years. I took the lisinopril every morning. Ate cleaner. Moved my body every single day without exception.</p><p>I did everything right. I did more than everything right.</p><p><strong>And I still felt wrong.</strong></p><p>A pressure behind my eyes every morning when I woke up. Headaches that sat there all day like a fist pressing against the back of my skull. An afternoon exhaustion that knocked into me like a wall, no matter how much sleep I got the night before. A mental fog I kept telling myself was just aging.</p><p>I kept thinking about my friend.</p><p>I kept wondering if I was on the same road. Just further back.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gghF9bVbstM_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"gghF9bVbstM_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/ChatGPT_Image_Mar_20_2026_04_23_48_PM.png"},{"type":"html","id":"gghF9bVbstM_srcSet_mobile_src","label":"gghF9bVbstM_srcSet_mobile_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_3.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggW6dewUfWq_text","label":"ggW6dewUfWq_text","default":"<p><strong>What Your Doctor Never Explained</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gga86PMY3n6_text","label":"gga86PMY3n6_text","default":"<p>That's when I started asking the question nobody in a doctor's office had ever answered for me.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i>If I'm doing everything right, why do I still feel like this?</i></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I found Reddit — women my age, same situation. On medication. Numbers controlled. Still exhausted. Still foggy. Still not right.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I read through hundreds of comments. The same story, different names, over and over.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That's where I first came across the real explanation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Here's what my doctor never told me. What most doctors never tell anyone.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Blood pressure medication does one thing. It brings the number down on the cuff.</p><p>That's it.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It doesn't fix what's actually happening inside your arteries. It never was designed to.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Here's what's actually happening:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>After 50, blood vessel walls start to stiffen.</strong> They lose their natural elasticity. The smooth muscle that lets them expand and relax starts to break down. The vessels become rigid. Hard. Like old garden hoses that have sat in the sun too long.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When blood tries to move through stiff vessels, it has to fight. The heart has to push harder. Pressure climbs.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg7IS3JCqAL_text","label":"gg7IS3JCqAL_text","default":"<p>That's when I started asking the question nobody in a doctor's office had ever answered for me.</p><p><i>If I'm doing everything right, why do I still feel like this?</i></p><p>I found Reddit — women my age, same situation. On medication. Numbers controlled. Still exhausted. Still foggy. Still not right.</p><p>I read through hundreds of comments. The same story, different names, over and over.</p><p>That's where I first came across the real explanation.</p><p><strong>Here's what my doctor never told me. What most doctors never tell anyone.</strong></p><p>Blood pressure medication does one thing. It brings the number down on the cuff.</p><p>That's it.</p><p>It doesn't fix what's actually happening inside your arteries. It never was designed to.</p><p>Here's what's actually happening:</p><p><strong>After 50, blood vessel walls start to stiffen.</strong> They lose their natural elasticity. The smooth muscle that lets them expand and relax starts to break down. The vessels become rigid. Hard. Like old garden hoses that have sat in the sun too long.</p><p>When blood tries to move through stiff vessels, it has to fight. The heart has to push harder. Pressure climbs.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggnQBvqU6k2_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggnQBvqU6k2_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_4.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggGsgmSWyrz_text","label":"ggGsgmSWyrz_text","default":"<p>Lisinopril and similar medications work like turning down the faucet. Less flow, less pressure. The number on the cuff drops.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>But the hose is still hard. The rigidity is still there. Nothing changed inside the artery wall.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That's why the headaches stay. That's why the fog stays. That's why the fatigue never actually lifts. The reading improved. The underlying problem didn't.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gggjDuuz6EG_text","label":"gggjDuuz6EG_text","default":"<p>Lisinopril and similar medications work like turning down the faucet. Less flow, less pressure. The number on the cuff drops.</p><p><strong>But the hose is still hard. The rigidity is still there. Nothing changed inside the artery wall.</strong></p><p>That's why the headaches stay. That's why the fog stays. That's why the fatigue never actually lifts. The reading improved. The underlying problem didn't.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggMJeaR9VCw_text","label":"ggMJeaR9VCw_text","default":"<p><strong>The Compound Your Prescription Can't Replace</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggyOi0AeG8l_text","label":"ggyOi0AeG8l_text","default":"<p><strong>The Compound Your Prescription Can't Replace</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg6B3JYDZHI_text","label":"gg6B3JYDZHI_text","default":"<p><strong>What the body actually needs is something called nitric oxide.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It's the compound your blood vessels use to relax and open up. When nitric oxide signals arrive at the vessel wall, the smooth muscle releases its tension. The artery expands. Blood flows freely. Pressure drops naturally, the way it was designed to.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>After 50, the body's ability to produce nitric oxide drops significantly.</strong> The system that kept your arteries flexible starts to fail. And nothing in a standard prescription restores it.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>No medication replaces nitric oxide. No standard blood pressure drug even tries.</p><p>The missing piece isn't a stronger drug. It's the compound that tells your vessels to relax in the first place.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggdQq29HQIr_text","label":"ggdQq29HQIr_text","default":"<p><strong>What the body actually needs is something called nitric oxide.</strong></p><p>It's the compound your blood vessels use to relax and open up. When nitric oxide signals arrive at the vessel wall, the smooth muscle releases its tension. The artery expands. Blood flows freely. Pressure drops naturally, the way it was designed to.</p><p><strong>After 50, the body's ability to produce nitric oxide drops significantly.</strong> The system that kept your arteries flexible starts to fail. And nothing in a standard prescription restores it.</p><p>No medication replaces nitric oxide. No standard blood pressure drug even tries.</p><p>The missing piece isn't a stronger drug. It's the compound that tells your vessels to relax in the first place.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg52MFmdg6y_text","label":"gg52MFmdg6y_text","default":"<p><strong>The Discovery That Changed Everything</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg4tAJ0t1Lw_text","label":"gg4tAJ0t1Lw_text","default":"<p><strong>The Discovery That Changed Everything</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggerYPCwqmD_text","label":"ggerYPCwqmD_text","default":"<p><strong>The most concentrated natural source of what the body uses to make nitric oxide is beetroot.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Beetroot is naturally high in inorganic nitrate.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The body converts that nitrate through a pathway that ends in nitric oxide production. Clinical research has documented this process. The arterial stiffness connection. The blood pressure response. The vascular flexibility.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggn-B4SYRIN_text","label":"ggn-B4SYRIN_text","default":"<p><strong>The most concentrated natural source of what the body uses to make nitric oxide is beetroot.</strong></p><p>Beetroot is naturally high in inorganic nitrate.&nbsp;</p><p>The body converts that nitrate through a pathway that ends in nitric oxide production. Clinical research has documented this process. The arterial stiffness connection. The blood pressure response. The vascular flexibility.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gggXYXY7wCZ_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"gggXYXY7wCZ_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_5.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggtfaV8s7iV_text","label":"ggtfaV8s7iV_text","default":"<p>I read the first study at midnight. Then another. Then another. I was up until 3am.</p><p>So I went looking for a beetroot supplement.</p><p><strong>I tried the first thing I could find. A powder from a local health store.</strong></p><p>Six weeks. Nothing changed. The morning pressure was still there. The fog was still there.</p><p>I switched to capsules. Higher dose on the label. Another two months. Still waking up with that dull pressure behind my eyes. Still reaching for ibuprofen by noon. Still crashing by afternoon.</p><p>I almost gave up on the entire idea. I started thinking maybe I was wrong. Maybe nothing was going to fix this.</p><p>Then a woman in the group, a retired nurse named Carol, messaged me directly.</p><p><strong>\"The ones you tried were heat-processed,\"</strong> she said. <strong>\"The heat destroys the active nitrate during manufacturing. Before it ever reaches your body.\"</strong></p><p>She said most beetroot supplements on the market are made this way. The nitrate, the compound the body uses to make nitric oxide, gets cooked out of the product in production. You swallow a capsule and absorb almost nothing.</p><p>That's why they don't work. Not because the mechanism is wrong. Because the product delivers nothing.</p><p>Carol told me there was one she had seen actually work.</p><p><strong>TrueNatural Pure Beetroot.</strong> A US company.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>1,300 mg of organic beetroot powder per serving, cold-processed to keep the active nitrate intact all the way through manufacturing and into the capsule.</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggffzrPsiEj_text","label":"ggffzrPsiEj_text","default":"<p>I read the first study at midnight. Then another. Then another. I was up until 3am.</p><p>So I went looking for a beetroot supplement.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>I tried the first thing I could find. A powder from a local health store.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Six weeks. Nothing changed. The morning pressure was still there. The fog was still there.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I switched to capsules. Higher dose on the label. Another two months. Still waking up with that dull pressure behind my eyes. Still reaching for ibuprofen by noon. Still crashing by afternoon.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I almost gave up on the entire idea. I started thinking maybe I was wrong. Maybe nothing was going to fix this.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Then a woman in the group, a retired nurse named Carol, messaged me directly.</p><p><strong>\"The ones you tried were heat-processed,\"</strong> she said. <strong>\"The heat destroys the active nitrate during manufacturing. Before it ever reaches your body.\"</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>She said most beetroot supplements on the market are made this way. The nitrate, the compound the body uses to make nitric oxide, gets cooked out of the product in production. You swallow a capsule and absorb almost nothing.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That's why they don't work. Not because the mechanism is wrong. Because the product delivers nothing.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Carol told me there was one she had seen actually work.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>TrueNatural Pure Beetroot.</strong> A US company.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>1,300 mg of organic beetroot powder per serving, cold-processed to keep the active nitrate intact all the way through manufacturing and into the capsule.</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggSkMvgHZ1r_srcSet_desktop_src","label":"ggSkMvgHZ1r_srcSet_desktop_src","default":"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0966/4040/1712/files/Thi_t_k_ch_a_co_ten_64d285db-2b1e-4cc0-826f-6c21699612e2.jpg"},{"type":"html","id":"ggmqBsYoyZR_text","label":"ggmqBsYoyZR_text","default":"<p>Cold-processed. That's the entire difference.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Not the brand. Not the dose on the label. Whether the nitrate survived the manufacturing process long enough to actually reach the body and do something.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>TrueNatural preserves it. Most others destroy it before you ever open the bottle.</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Just two capsules a day. 1,300 mg. Organic. Cold-processed.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I ordered it.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggq1-iF3esS_text","label":"ggq1-iF3esS_text","default":"<p><strong>Then This Happened</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1C_2PPc8c_text","label":"gg1C_2PPc8c_text","default":"<p>Cold-processed. That's the entire difference.</p><p>Not the brand. Not the dose on the label. Whether the nitrate survived the manufacturing process long enough to actually reach the body and do something.</p><p><strong>TrueNatural preserves it. Most others destroy it before you ever open the bottle.</strong></p><p>Just two capsules a day. 1,300 mg. Organic. Cold-processed.</p><p>I ordered it.</p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggZ9oJUQmkJ_text","label":"ggZ9oJUQmkJ_text","default":"<p><strong>Then This Happened</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1c22cJdMk_text","label":"gg1c22cJdMk_text","default":"<p>I kept doing everything else I was already doing. The hiking. The clean eating. The medication. I added this one thing.</p><p><strong>Within three weeks, the morning pressure behind my eyes started to ease.</strong></p><p>By the end of the first month, the 